        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Configuration:
We request any configuration capable of delivering angular resolution better than 1''. The two bright and compact lensed images of the blazar are separated by 0.3'', with well known relative positions from VLBI observations. Hence (as for Cycle 0 data on PKS1830-211), we will self-calibrate the data and perform visibility fitting to extract the spectra toward each image. The signal-to-noise ratio will be sufficient for the visibility fitting to separate both blazar images, even on a spectral channel basis.
We reckon that the ALMA beam will be slightly elongated in the NS direction, due to the low elevation of the source from ALMA site. This is not a big concern, since the two images are split in the EW direction.

Spectral setup:
We request three basebands to cover the lines of HCO+, HCN, and HNC, with velocity resolution of ~0.5 km/s (the deepest velocity component is about 5 km/s wide). This is best achieved with spectral windows of 468 MHz (wide enough to cover the line and give continuum signal) and a spectral averaging by factor of 2 (which will also decrease the data rate without compromising the velocity resolution). In addition, we request one more baseband to cover the HOC+ 3-2 line, with 1 km/s velocity resolution (we expect the line to be weak).

Requested sensitivity:
We estimate the flux density F(A) and F(B) of the two blazar images A and B as F = F0 (nu/nu0)^-alpha. We take alpha=0.7, F0(A)=0.4 Jy at 100 GHz (based on our previous PdBI observations), and a magnification ratio A/B=4. This gives F(A)=0.29 Jy and F(B)=0.07 Jy for this tuning. We target a sensitivity of 1 sigma on 1% of the continuum level (ie on tau=1%) toward image A (where the absorption occurs), that is 2.9 mJy, for a velocity resolution of 1 km/s (sufficient to get the line integrated opacities).
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
