    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Determining the cosmic microwave background temperature (T_CMB) at high redshift has considerable interest to demonstrate that the CMB is universal and to probe the CMB temperature evolution with redshift. It is also a crucial test for decaying dark energy models, which predict a slightly different temperature evolution than standard cosmology. We have recently obtain a precise and accurate measurement of T_CMB=5.08+-0.10 K at (ie 2% uncertainty) at z=0.89 in the molecular absorber toward the blazar PKS1830-211. This value is consistent with adiabatic expansion of the Universe. 
We now propose to similarly measure T_CMB at z=0.68, in the molecular absorber toward the blazar B0218+357. The absorbing gas in this sightline is known to be more diffuse than toward PKS1830-211, therefore providing an even better radiative coupling of the molecules with the CMB photons. Based on the results of our Monte-Carlo simulations, we target a precision of 1--2% on T_CMB, yielding the most precise measurement of T_CMB in a source at z&gt;0.
</prp:abstract>
